      <body>
         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <expan><abbr>L</abbr><ex>ucius</ex></expan> Flavius
                <lb n="2"/>
               <expan><abbr>Sal</abbr><ex cert="low">vi</ex></expan>
               <supplied reason="subaudible">filius</supplied>
               <expan><abbr>Pom</abbr><ex cert="low">ptina</ex></expan>.</ab>
            <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Lucius Flavius, son of Salvius, from the Pomptina (tribe).</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The reverse shows traces of a scroll that has been incompletely erased,
               indicating the reuse of the piece for this inscription. (Tuck)</p>
            <p>The form of the name is highly unusual and it is therefore difficult to expand the
               abbreviations with certainty. The palaeography is Republican, which would lend itself
               to the expansion <hi rend="italic">L(ucius) Flavius Sal(vi) (scil. filius) Pom(ptina)</hi> as the formula of
               filiation followed by tribe name points to a date in the late first century BCE.
               However, <hi rend="italic">Salvius</hi> was a Republican <hi rend="italic">nomen</hi>, so the resulting mismatch between <hi rend="italic">Flavius</hi>
               and <hi rend="italic">Salvius</hi> would be unusual. But, the fact that the columbarium slab was found
               outside the Porta Salaria, that it is made of marble, and that it shows signs of
               reuse point to a more Imperial date in the first century CE. It was not unusual for
               columbaria in the early Imperial period to preserve name and occupation, hence
               another possible expansion, as suggested by Solin, is <hi rend="italic">L(ucius) Flavius Sal(vius)
               pom(arius)</hi>, which is still unusual. </p>
            <p>Line 2: Sal(vius) Pom(ptina tribu) (Baldwin); Sal(vius) pom(arius) (Tuck)</p>
         </div>
